3.00	Bitterwood	Quassia amara	Quassia amara is a species in the genus Quassia, with some botanists treating it as the sole species in the genus. It is a shrub or rarely a small tree, growing to 3 m tall (rarely 8 m), native to Brazil. The leaves are compound and alternate, 15-25 cm long, and pinnate with 3-5 leaflets, the leaf rachis being winged. The flowers are produced in a panicle 15-25 cm long, each flower 2.5-3.5 cm long, bright red on the outside, and white inside. The fruit is a small drupe 1-1.5 cm long. Q. amara is widely planted outside its native range.	http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/4/44/Quassia_amara_-_K%C3%B6hler%E2%80%93s_Medizinal-Pflanzen-117.jpg/220px-Quassia_amara_-_K%C3%B6hler%E2%80%93s_Medizinal-Pflanzen-117.jpg
